Task 1: IBM knows you are leaving

Trying to predict the risk of loosing an employee is critical if you want to keep talent within your company and avoid having a high turnover rate. For this task, you will be working with data from a company which contains information about employees and whether they left the company or not.

employees <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/data/hw6/employee_attrition.csv") %>% select(-c(EmployeeCount, Over18, StandardHours))

Note: We remove three variables that have no variation in this dataset.

You can see a codebook of the variables here

Our goal is to best predict whether an employee will leave their company or not, given their characteristics.

Question 1.1

Let’s start preparing our data. (a) Transform the variables Education, EnvironmentSatisfaction, JobInvolvement, JobSatisfaction, PerformanceRating, RelationshipSatisfaction, and WorkLifeBalance to categorical variables; and (b) split our data 70-30 for training and testing purposes.

Answer: 

set.seed(100)

employees <- employees %>% mutate(across(c(Education, EnvironmentSatisfaction,

Question 1.3

Build a classification tree using 10-fold cross-validation. Show an appropriate plot for identifying the optimal hyper-parameter and also a plot of your tree.

Answer: We will run a model using all our covariates. We set a grid for the tuning parameter between 0 and 0.2, after exploring other values.


library(caret)
library(rattle)

set.seed(100)

ct <- train(
  factor(Attrition) ~., data = train.data,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(cp = seq(0, 0.2, by = 0.001))
)

We can see from the plot below that the optimal value lays between 0.02 and 0.05, and it’s actually 0.035.

plot(ct)

In terms of plotting our tree, we can see that we get three different splits: Total working years, distance from home, and age 

library(rattle)

fancyRpartPlot(ct$finalModel, caption = "Classification tree for predicting attrition")

Task 2: Making News Popular

You are working at an online news outlet and have been assigned the task of maximizing user engagement in your platform. For that reason, you start analyzing previous data from the site to understand better what makes a story more engaging from a user-experience perspective:

news <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/data/hw6/news.csv")

You can see a codebook of the variables here

In this case, you are interested in predicting the number of shares that an article will have.

Question 2.1

Create a regression tree to predict the number of shares an article will have based on its characteristics. (a) Show an appropriate plot for your complexity parameter, as well as the number itself; (b) How does your model perform? (Note: Remove any variables that are not predictors, and use the standard arguments we have used for prediction models so far in class).

Answer: First, we create a training and testing dataset as defined below, and we drop both url and timedelta from the dataset, as they will not serve as predictors.


set.seed(100)

news <- news %>% select(-c(url, timedelta))

n <- nrow(news)

train <- sample(1:n, 0.8*n)

train.data <- news %>% slice(train)
test.data <- news %>% slice(-train)

Now, we will fit a regression tree: 

set.seed(100)

rt <- train(
  shares ~ ., data = train.data,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(cp = seq(0,0.08, length = 100))
)

We can see the optimal complexity parameter is 0.0315152. In this case, the complexity parameter is high enough that we are just obtaining a root.


plot(rt)


fancyRpartPlot(rt$finalModel, caption = "Regression Tree for News Shares")

The RMSE for this model is 6654.92, which is not a great RMSE given that the mean of the outcome is 3,035 shares.


library(modelr)

rmse(rt, test.data)

Question 2.4

Using your original dataset news, create a categorical variable named performance that takes the value of 1 if the article doesn’t do well (bottom 25% of the distribution), 2 if it does ok (between the 25th and 75th percentile), and 3 if it becomes viral (top 25%).

Create a classification tree for this variable, but remember to remove shares from your predictors (no need to show the tree in your write-up). (a) Show both your complexity parameter in a plot, what do you find? (b) Which is the most predictive covariate? How do you find it? (c) How accurate are your predictions by category? (Note: Consider that the bottom and top of the distribution include the 25th and 75th percentile, respectively)

Answer: First, we create our variable as well as our testing and training dataset 

p75 <- quantile(news$shares, probs = 0.75)
p25 <- quantile(news$shares, probs = 0.25)

set.seed(100)

news <- news %>% mutate(performance = ifelse(shares<=p25, 1,
                                             ifelse(shares>=p75, 3, 2))) %>%
  mutate(performance = factor(performance, labels = c("Bad", "OK", "Viral")))

n <- nrow(news)

train <- sample(1:n, 0.8*n)

train.data <- news %>% slice(train)
test.data <- news %>% slice(-train)

Then, we fit a classification tree, and get an optimal complexity parameter of 0.0025, and looking at ct2$finalModel, we see that the variable we use for the first split is kw_avg_avg, which is Avg. keyword (avg. shares). 

set.seed(100)

ct2 <- train(
  performance ~ . - shares, data = train.data,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl("cv", number = 10),
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(cp = seq(0,0.05, length = 100))
)


plot(ct2)

Our accuracy for this model is 0.492, and we can see that we do not do a great job predicting the bottom or top categories, and we tend to classify every news article as doing OK.

pred.category <- ct2 %>% predict(test.data)
test.data <- test.data %>% mutate(prediction = pred.category)

acc <- mean(test.data$performance == test.data$prediction)

test.data %>% select(performance, prediction) %>% table %>% 
  proportions(., margin = 1) %>% round(., 3)

##       Viral 0.043 0.797 0.160

Question 2.5

Talking to the advertising team, they tell you that they promote stories equally, but if they see a story that has gotten over 10,000 shares in the previous week, they take new actions to try to bump it up even more (e.g. increase promotions in Twitter, paid advertising on Facebook, among others). Given this new knowledge and using existing data in the company, how could you design a study to estimate a causal effect of these interventions? Explain. What is the estimand that you would be able to recover?

Answer: In this case, knowing that there is a threshold of 10,000 shares, we could conduct a regression discontinuity design, where we would compare stories right at the threshold of 10,000 shares. In this case, we could analyze shares in week (t+1) using shares in week t as the running variable. In this case, the estimand we would be able to obtain is a Local Average Treatment Effect (LATE), meaning an estimate of the effect of all these interventions for articles with exactly 10,000 shares.


  • 100%: Correctly identifies an RD design and explains the running variable and the outcome. Identifies the correct estimand as a LATE.

  • 80%: Correctly identifies an RD design, but doesn’t properly identify the running variable/the outcome, or doesn’t identify the correct estimand.

  • 50%: Correctly identifies an RD design, but have problems idenfying all key elements.

  • 20%: Tries something that makes some sense, but overall incorrect.

  • 0%: Any other case.
